    "english": [
      "Hi, how are you doing?",
      "Hey. So I wanted to reach out to you because I saw this ad yesterday. It was from, like, a retirement home or something, and they're basically looking for volunteers to help with some of their activities that they do, like reading workshops for seniors, computer workshops and just fun activities like card games, chess, stuff like that. And it sounds like they're looking for volunteers. And I wanted to reach out to you when I saw this ad because you mentioned to me about how you were looking for something new to do in your spare time, and you were looking for a new experience of some sort. I've never done something like this before, and I'm not sure if you have, but I just thought this might be something fun for both of us to do. It will be kind of like a new experience. So I'm just calling to see if you're down for something like this.",
      "Right. Yeah, I guess volunteering isn't really the most exciting thing that you can do. But this doesn't need to be-- we don't need to commit to this. Right? Like, I'm not saying this should be the new weekly thing that we do. Of course not. We can try it just for once. I mean, like, I don't really see a problem with just trying it just for once because it's not gonna take us a lot of time. And we get a different flavor of a new experience. Like, for example, the new experience of doing sth like snowboarding, that's one flavor of a new experience, but this is a different flavor, and I think in life, it's not only important to try new things, but also to try different flavors of new experiences.",
      "Right. I'm reading your response as that you don't think this will be worth your time. But I think it can be worth our time because first of all, we really don't need to... I know I'm repeating myself, but we really don't need to do this for a second time if we don't want to. I think we should at least try it once though, because... Have you volunteered before? I haven't. I don't know what it would be like. I've always wondered what it would be like, because it's an activity you do more often than not for others' sake and not for your own, and I've always wondered how fulfilling it could feel. And I think these experiences in general, where we help others with nothing to gain ourselves, open up doors and fires up neurons in our brains that we don't know exist and make us think of new ideas, new ways of seeing life, and new perspectives. And also, these people are-- they're seniors and they need help and whatever, but they also have decades of experience which are really useful, and you never know what you could learn from being around these people and just talking to them. As a regular thing, doing this over months, sure, we can debate whether it's worth our time or not, but for one afternoon, I think it's definitely worth our time.",
      "Sure. Sure. I guess. But also, this puts us in the position where we're not comfortable, and I feel like we need to get out of our comfort zone sometimes You never know what we would end up doing. We might have to organize activities ourselves. We might have to deal with people who do not necessarily like us. And it's uncomfortable, right? But it also teaches us how to just wing it in these scenarios where we're like against the wall. And I think that skill of winging it, knowing that we have done this before, will really help us later down the line with our careers and so on and so forth, where we're asked to do something that we have no experience of, that we don't particularly like, that makes us uncomfortable. We'll know that we have the muscle inside of us that we can flex in those scenarios, and I think that will be really helpful for us. So that's why I think it will be worth our time.",
      "I see. Okay. That's a good point. But again, going back to my point about new flavors of experiences, right? You are able to deal with these uncomfortable scenarios in your part-time job because you are doing it for money, and something's at stake. In this scenario, what's at stake isn't yourself, but maybe what's at stake is the people around you. So maybe that fires up a different side of your brain. The fact that you're in an uncomfortable scenario that you don't have to be in, nothing's at stake for yourself... You can immediately just get out, right? It's volunteering. What are they gonna do? Fire us? We're not getting paid, right? So you're not the one at stake here, but someone else is. Maybe they are the ones who are at stake. These people who might be vulnerable. So how do you react in those sort of scenarios, right? What do you do? That's a different kind of experience, and I feel like that's really interesting to navigate around, and yeah, that's why I was really interested in this.",
      "Right. That's a concern that I also frankly have. But that's why I wanna do this, right? Because it makes us learn something new. It not only makes us learn these skills like these tangible skills like event organization, activity organization, communication, but also helps us learn emotional intelligence. It makes us build empathy with people. And yes, that's a valid point that we're not cut out for this, but it's like... I don't know. I feel like putting ourselves in high pressure scenarios is important sometimes. But the thing with this is it is high pressure, but the stakes are not also like high enough, right? There'll be people around us to support us, right? They're not just gonna let random strangers, kids who are like 20 years old, without any experience dealing with seniors, to just go do whatever. There'll be supervisors around us, mentoring us, guiding us. So there's a safety net underneath us, so it's safe enough to fail but also high-pressure enough for us to grow.",
      "Right. Yeah, think about this, and let me know what you think."
    ],
